  <page>
   <exercise>
  <title>Differentiation of Polynomial and Radical Expressions</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the derivatives of the following functions:
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>p(x) = \sqrt{x} - \sqrt{2} + x^2 - \pi^2</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y = \displaystyle \frac{x^3 + 5x^2 - 2}{x^2}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          <p>
            Rewrite the radical as a power: <m>p(x) = x^{1/2} - \sqrt{2} + x^2 - \pi^2</m>. Note that <m>\sqrt{2}</m> and <m>\pi^2</m> are constants, so their derivatives are <m>0</m>.
            <me>p'(x) = \frac{1}{2}x^{-1/2} + 2x = \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}} + 2x</me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            First, simplify the expression by dividing each term in the numerator by <m>x^2</m>:
            <me>y = \frac{x^3}{x^2} + \frac{5x^2}{x^2} - \frac{2}{x^2} = x + 5 - 2x^{-2}</me>
            Now, differentiate using the power rule:
            <me>y' = 1 + 0 - 2(-2x^{-3}) = 1 + \frac{4}{x^3}</me>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Higher Order Derivatives</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the <term>first and second derivatives</term> of <m>\displaystyle y = 3x^3 - \frac{1}{x}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Rewrite the function: <m>y = 3x^3 - x^{-1}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The first derivative is:
      <me>y' = 3(3x^2) - (-1x^{-2}) = 9x^2 + \frac{1}{x^2}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      To find the second derivative, differentiate <m>y' = 9x^2 + x^{-2}</m>:
      <me>y'' = 9(2x) + (-2x^{-3}) = 18x - \frac{2}{x^3}</me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Differentiability of the Absolute Value Function</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that <m>f(x) = |x|</m> is not differentiable at <m>0</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      To show <m>f(x)</m> is not differentiable at <m>x=0</m>, we check the limit definition of the derivative:
      <me>f'(0) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(0+h) - f(0)}{h} = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{|h| - 0}{h} = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{|h|}{h}</me>
      We examine the one-sided limits:
      <ul>
        <li><p>From the right (<m>h \gt 0</m>): <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \to 0^+} \frac{h}{h} = 1</m></p></li>
        <li><p>From the left (<m>h \lt 0</m>): <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \to 0^-} \frac{-h}{h} = -1</m></p></li>
      </ul>
      Since the one-sided limits are not equal, the limit does not exist. Thus, <m>f(x)</m> is <term>not differentiable</term> at <m>x=0</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

  </page>


</worksheet>
